I think this means two things and you can't quite see it right away.

There are two scenarios: there is no match, so the string has to be broken into two parts. Then there is a match, so the remainder part has to be kept. But this is also only if the pattern would not also produce another match. So, if it produces another match, the remaining part has to be kept. This can be simplified like so:
In the first case you have either a first or second match, meaning you have to break the string up before you match on the whole pattern. If you look at the other pattern (\w+\w*), you see that the remaining part has at the most \w*, but some characters might be longer. You then have to use an additional \w+ to allow for characters longer than \w*.
